Sure! Below is an example of a script that allows a 2D sprite object to move left and right in Unity.

```C#
using UnityEngine;

public class SpriteMovement : MonoBehaviour
{
    public float moveSpeed = 5f; // The speed at which the sprite moves

    private Rigidbody2D rb; // Reference to the Rigidbody2D component

    // Start is called before the first frame update
    private void Start()
    {
        rb = GetComponent<Rigidbody2D>(); // Get the Rigidbody2D component attached to the sprite object
    }

    // Update is called once per frame
    private void Update()
    {
        float moveX = Input.GetAxis("Horizontal"); // Get the horizontal input axis (left/right arrow or A/D keys)

        Vector2 movement = new Vector2(moveX, 0f); // Create a movement vector

        rb.velocity = movement * moveSpeed; // Update the velocity of the sprite's Rigidbody2D component
    }
}
```

To use this script, simply follow these steps:

1. Attach it to the sprite object in your Unity scene.
2. Make sure the sprite object has a Rigidbody2D component attached to it.
3. Adjust the "moveSpeed" variable to your desired movement speed.

Now, when you run the game, you should be able to use the left and right arrow keys (or A and D keys) to move the sprite in the respective directions along the x-axis.

