To use the `AddForce` method in Unity, you need to have a Rigidbody component attached to the GameObject you want to apply force to. Here's an example of how to use `AddForce` to apply force to a Rigidbody:

```C#
using UnityEngine;

public class ApplyForce : MonoBehaviour
{
    public float forceMagnitude = 10f; // The magnitude of the force to apply

    private Rigidbody rb; // Reference to the Rigidbody component

    // Start is called before the first frame update
    private void Start()
    {
        rb = GetComponent<Rigidbody>(); // Get the Rigidbody component attached to the GameObject
    }

    // Update is called once per frame
    private void Update()
    {
        if (Input.GetKeyDown(KeyCode.Space))
        {
            // Apply the force in a random direction
            Vector3 forceDirection = new Vector3(Random.Range(-1f, 1f), Random.Range(-1f, 1f), Random.Range(-1f, 1f));
            forceDirection = forceDirection.normalized; // Normalize the direction vector

            // Apply the force to the Rigidbody
            rb.AddForce(forceDirection * forceMagnitude, ForceMode.Impulse);
        }
    }
}
```

In this example, the `AddForce` method is used within the `Update` function. Whenever the Space key is pressed, it applies a random force direction and magnitude to the Rigidbody component attached to the object.

Adjust the `forceMagnitude` value to control the strength of the force being applied. You can also modify the `Update` function to apply force under specific conditions or in response to different input events according to your requirements.

Remember to attach this script to a GameObject that has a Rigidbody component to see the force being applied.

